To convert a string in Solidity (stored in memory) to `bytes32`, you can use the `bytes` type to cast the string and then truncate or pad it to the desired length.

Here's an example function that converts a string to `bytes32`:

```solidity
function stringToBytes32(string memory text) pure returns (bytes32 result) {
    require(bytes(text).length <= 32, "String too long for bytes32");

    assembly {
        // Allocate a fixed-size memory buffer
        let mem := mload(0x40)

        // Set the length of the bytes object to the length of the string
        mstore(mem, mload(text))

        // Copy the string to the memory buffer
        mstore(add(mem, 0x20), text)

        // Store the result as bytes32
        result := mload(mem)
    }
}
```

In this example, the function takes a string `text` as a parameter and checks if the length of the string is within the maximum 32 bytes limit. If it exceeds the limit, it throws an error.

The assembly block is used to allocate a fixed-size memory buffer, set its length to the length of the string, copy the string into the buffer, and finally store the result as `bytes32`.

You can then call this function to convert a string to `bytes32`:

```solidity
string myString = "Hello, World!";
bytes32 myBytes32 = stringToBytes32(myString);
```

Note that if the input string is shorter than 32 bytes, the remaining bytes in the `bytes32` variable will be padded with zeros.

